<keyStep pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,991,1054]" box="[189,1399,991,1019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<keyLead box="[189,1399,991,1019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
1. Pronotum dirty orange, with distinct punctures (
<figureCitation box="[798,890,992,1018]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="43.[189,232,1894,1920]" captionTargetBox="[255,1348,414,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-12@43.[189,1398,376,1856]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Fig. 2. Habitus of Ernestinus, Harpedona and Lopidolon spp. A. Ernestinus mimicus Distant, 1911, ♂, UASB. B. Ernestinus ramkeshariae Yasunaga &amp; Ishikawa, 2016, ♂, UASB. C. Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1904, ♂, UASB. D. Harpedona vittlaensis sp. nov, ♀, UASB. E–F. Lopidolon dandeliensis sp. nov., UASB. E. ♂. F. ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690366/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
) ................................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Yeshwanth &amp; Konstantinov, 2021" authorityName="Yeshwanth &amp; Konstantinov" authorityYear="2021" box="[1143,1301,991,1018]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Harpedona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittlaensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1143,1301,991,1018]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">H. vittlaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1308,1399,993,1019]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,991,1054]" box="[193,1399,1027,1054]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<keyLead box="[193,1399,1027,1054]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[193,208,1028,1053]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">–</emphasis>
Pronotum dark brown, smooth or very faintly punctate (
<figureCitation box="[890,986,1027,1054]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="43.[189,232,1894,1920]" captionTargetBox="[255,1348,414,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-12@43.[189,1398,376,1856]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Fig. 2. Habitus of Ernestinus, Harpedona and Lopidolon spp. A. Ernestinus mimicus Distant, 1911, ♂, UASB. B. Ernestinus ramkeshariae Yasunaga &amp; Ishikawa, 2016, ♂, UASB. C. Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1904, ♂, UASB. D. Harpedona vittlaensis sp. nov, ♀, UASB. E–F. Lopidolon dandeliensis sp. nov., UASB. E. ♂. F. ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690366/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs 2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[999,1058,1027,1054]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="46.[189,232,1824,1850]" captionTargetBox="[263,1330,330,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-17@46.[189,1398,297,1786]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Fig. 5. Dorsal view and label data of type specimens. A–C. Dioclerus bengalicus Stonedahl, 1988, ♀, holotype, BPBM.D–E. Dioclerus lutheri Stonedahl, 1988, ♂, holotype, AMNH_PBI 00338430, FMNH. F–G. Dioclerus praefectus Distant,1910, lectotype, AMNH_PBI 00340384, NHM. H–I. Ernestinus mimicus Distant,1911, ♂, syntype, AMNH_PBI 00085668, BMNH(E) 1633157, NHM. J–K. Harpedona marginata Distant, 1904, ♂, holotype, NHM. L–M. Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1909, ♂, lectotype, NHM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690372/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">5J, L</figureCitation>
) ......................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,1093,1262]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<keyLead pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
2. Frons in males with a distinct longitudinal sulcus (
<figureCitation box="[851,938,1093,1120]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="46.[189,232,1824,1850]" captionTargetBox="[263,1330,330,1736]" captionTargetId="figure-17@46.[189,1398,297,1786]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Fig. 5. Dorsal view and label data of type specimens. A–C. Dioclerus bengalicus Stonedahl, 1988, ♀, holotype, BPBM.D–E. Dioclerus lutheri Stonedahl, 1988, ♂, holotype, AMNH_PBI 00338430, FMNH. F–G. Dioclerus praefectus Distant,1910, lectotype, AMNH_PBI 00340384, NHM. H–I. Ernestinus mimicus Distant,1911, ♂, syntype, AMNH_PBI 00085668, BMNH(E) 1633157, NHM. J–K. Harpedona marginata Distant, 1904, ♂, holotype, NHM. L–M. Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1909, ♂, lectotype, NHM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690372/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 5J</figureCitation>
). Labium at most reaching mesocoxa. Femora pale yellow. Phallotheca with a large sclerotized sac (
<figureCitation box="[957,1064,1128,1155]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="55.[189,232,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[310,1285,295,1867]" captionTargetId="figure-52@55.[227,1360,265,1889]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="Fig. 14. Male genitalia of Harpedona marginata Distant, 1904, NHM. A–C. Genital capsule in ventral and lateral views. D–E. Right paramere in dorsal and lateral views. F. Right paramere in dorsal view. G. Aedeagus in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690392" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690392/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 14G</figureCitation>
) .......................................... ................................................................................................................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Distant, 1904" authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1904" box="[1070,1399,1164,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Harpedona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1070,1234,1164,1190]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">H. marginata</emphasis>
Distant, 1904
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[189,1399,1093,1262]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<keyLead pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis box="[193,208,1200,1225]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">–</emphasis>
Frons without sulcus. Labium surpassing metacoxae. Femora with a distinct reddish tinge (
<figureCitation box="[1293,1385,1199,1226]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="43.[189,232,1894,1920]" captionTargetBox="[255,1348,414,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-12@43.[189,1398,376,1856]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Fig. 2. Habitus of Ernestinus, Harpedona and Lopidolon spp. A. Ernestinus mimicus Distant, 1911, ♂, UASB. B. Ernestinus ramkeshariae Yasunaga &amp; Ishikawa, 2016, ♂, UASB. C. Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1904, ♂, UASB. D. Harpedona vittlaensis sp. nov, ♀, UASB. E–F. Lopidolon dandeliensis sp. nov., UASB. E. ♂. F. ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690366/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Phallotheca membranous, without a sclerotized sac (
<figureCitation box="[849,992,1235,1262]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="56.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[209,1328,425,1859]" captionTargetId="figure-57@56.[189,1398,401,1890]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="Fig. 15. Male genitalia of Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1904, UASB. A–B. Genital capsule in dorsal and ventral views. C–D. Left paramere in lateral view. E–F. Right paramere in dorsal view. G–H. Aedeagus in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690395" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690395/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 15G–H</figureCitation>
) ..... 
